1. Introduction¶

This notebook reflects the analysis done for the project three (3), a requirement for the Udacity-Data Analyst Program. This project is aimed at solidfying the knowledge gained during the Data Exploratory & Explanatory lectures offered in the classroom. Thus, this notebook will involve the exploration and visualization of a dataset to be discussed below.

1.1. Brief Explanation of the Dataset.¶

There are several datasets provided to complete this project. I will be working with the Ford GoBike System Data. This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

1.2. Summary of Tools/ Libraries needed for the Exploration¶

In this project, the major tool/libraries needed include the following:
  • Pandas: This is a python library which handles data manipulation and data wrangling. It helps to view data in DataFrames & Series. It could be used for simple/quick viusualizations
  • NumPy: NumPy is a Numerical Python library, used for dealing with data in arrays and several dimensions
  • Matplotlib: Matplotlib is a python library used basically for visualization of data.
  • Seaborn: Seaborn is used for a more interactive visualizations, and for beautifying visualizations.

2. Data Wrangling¶

This section cuts across, the import of needed libraries, data understanding, accessing the dataset, & cleaning the data

2.4. Cleaning the Errors from the Data¶

In [8]:
# Making a copy of the dataset

bike_data_clean = bike_data.copy()

I. start_time & end_time have date & time together, which is not a good fit for data entry.

Define¶

Extraction of time from date in the start_time & end_time columns

Code¶

In [9]:
# Let's define a functions for the Operation
def extract_time(time, col):
    # code for extraction of time
    bike_data_clean[time] = pd.to_datetime(bike_data_clean[col]).dt.time
    
def extract_date(date, col):
    # code for extraction of date
    bike_data_clean[date] = pd.to_datetime(bike_data_clean[col]).dt.date
In [10]:
# Extracting the time
extract_time('Start_time', 'start_time')
extract_time('End_time', 'end_time')
In [11]:
# Extracting the date
extract_date('Start_date', 'start_time')
extract_date('End_date', 'end_time')
In [12]:
# Let's drop the start_time & end_time columns as they may not be useful anymore
bike_data_clean = bike_data_clean.drop(columns=['start_time', 'end_time'])

In [22]:
# calculating the percentage of the gender of the members involved
total_member = bike_data_clean['member_gender'].value_counts().sum()
male_percentage = round((bike_data_clean['member_gender'].value_counts()[0]/ total_member) * 100, 2)
female_percentage = round((bike_data_clean['member_gender'].value_counts()[1]/ total_member) * 100, 2)
others_percentage = round((bike_data_clean['member_gender'].value_counts()[2]/ total_member) * 100, 2)
In [23]:
# Let's define a list for the gender 
plt.style.use('seaborn')
gender = ['Male', 'Female', 'Others']
# Let's define a list for the percentage of the gender
gender_percentage = [male_percentage, female_percentage, others_percentage]

n = 3
r = np.arange(n)
plt.bar(r, gender_percentage, color='#1F3F49')

plt.xlabel('Gender', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Gender Members', fontsize=15)
plt.title('Percentage Count of Members', fontsize=15)
plt.xticks(r, gender)
#plt.yaxis.set_axis(False)
for i in range(len(r)):
    plt.text(i, gender_percentage[i], gender_percentage[i])

Observation¶

  • From the Barplot above we will observe the percentage ratio of the members
  • 74.59% of the members are Male
  • 23.32% of the members are Female
  • 2.08% of the members are either males or females
  • This is indicative of the fact that we have more of the males as members of the bike sharing systems

i. Let's Visualize the bike id relationship to the duration with respect to the birth year of the members¶

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
plt.scatter(data=bike_data_clean, x='bike_id', y='duration_sec', c='member_birth_year', cmap = 'viridis', s=5)

plt.title('Relationship between Bike_id & duration of trip', fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel('Duration (sec)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Bike ID', fontsize=14);

Observation¶

  • From the plot we infer that it took lesser time for most of the bikes to complete the trip
  • Members with higher birth rate dominated the trip.
